§ SEC:named_section
Introduction

¶ PAR:named_paragraph

According to [DEF:provability] ...

This is a no-markup-markup document, sporting the following cool features:

[]	*Emphasized text
	spanning multiple
	lines in the source code without breaking a sweat*.

[]	Bullet lists:

	-	Here is one bullet item.

	-	Here is another one.

[]	Numbered lists with labels that are either

	[]	automatic, or

	[*]	custom.

	Furthermore, each item can be *named* and *referred
	to*:

	[]	ITM:x
		The named item can be referred to anywhere in the document.

	[]	ITM:y
		When referring to [ITM:x] above in a local manner (which is default), any common initial path shared between the location of the referring expression and the location of its referent will be omitted. The same applies with respect to [ITM:z] below.

	[†]	ITM:z
		Of course, items with custom labels can also be named!

Due to the feature mentioned in [ITM:y], a local reference to [ITM:x] or [ITM:z] occurring elsewhere may appear differently.

[]	Displayed lines of text suitable for mathematical equations, which are either

	()	automatically labeled (and named),	DSP:one
	(+)	custom labeled (and named), or,
		unlike [DSP:one] above, unlabeled.

Displayed lines can also be used for drawing tables and such:

	    |    0    |      1      |    2      | . . .
	───────────────────────────────────────────────
	f₀  | f₀(0) + 1 | f₀(1)     | f₀(2)     |
	f₁  | f₁(0)     | f₁(1) + 1 | f₁(2)     |
	f₂  | f₂(0)     | f₂(1)     | f₂(2) + 1 |
	.                                         .
	.                                           .
	.                                             .

This is what a reference to [DSP:one] looks like.

¶

We may also refer to [ITM:x] or [ITM:y] from another paragraph. These references will appear differently than when occurring in paragraph [PAR:named_paragraph] above.

This is what a reference to [DSP:one] looks like.

§
Section headers are optional, but recommended. They may contain both *emphasized text* and references, neither of which are recommended.

¶

The same goes for paragraph headers. As we shall see in [PAR:named_paragraph_with_header] below, paragraphs with headers can also be named.

¶ PAR:named_paragraph_with_header
This is a *paragraph header*, referencing [ITM:x] and [ITM:y] above. Again, these references will appear differently than when occurring in [PAR:named_paragraph].

Putting references in a header does not look very nice.

¶ DEF:semcons

We say that Γ ⊨ φ just in case every model of Γ is a model of φ.

¶ DEF:provability
Provability

We say that Γ ⊢ φ just in case there is a proof from Γ to φ.

¶ FCT:compl

For every sentence φ and set of sentences Γ, if Γ ⊨ φ then Γ ⊢ φ.
